<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920117-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>920117-0036.</DOCID><HL>   Sandamp;L Bailout Agency   Expects Indictments   Over Home Purchases</HL><DATE>01/17/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>ARIZONA (AZ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The savings-and-loan bailout agency expectsseveral indictments in coming months of home buyers whomasquerade as low-income people in order to purchase homesset aside for the poor.   Forrest Burdick, a real estate agent in Phoenix, Ariz.,was indicted Wednesday by a federal grand jury, according toClark Blight, assistant inspector general of the ResolutionTrust Corp., in the first case involving fraud in theagency's affordable housing program.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We have a number of these cases around the country,&quot; saidMr. Blight, &quot;and we expect more indictments.&quot;   According to the indictment, Mr. Burdick filed 12 sealedbids for homes that were limited to low-income buyers. Usingthe names of three people who never intended to purchase theproperty, and false financial information, he won title tothree homes from the agency, the RTC said.   Mr. Burdick didn't return a call seeking comment on theindictment. If convicted on all counts, he could be sentencedto 10 years, and $100,000 in fines, Mr. Blight said.   The agency, which sells the assets from failed Sandamp;Ls, mustset aside any homes with a value of less than $67,500 for 90days, to allow nonprofit organizations and low-income peopleto bid first for them. The low-income homes come with certaindeed restrictions, including a requirement that the buyerlive in the property for at least a year.   The agency currently has about $141 billion in assets.Real estate represents about $17 billion of the assets,including roughly 20,000 single-family homes.</TEXT></DOC>